nd":"Croft Ambrey, Herefordshire, England"},"en":{"1162–1213":"1162–1213","1220–1262":"1220–1262","1235–1318":"1235–1318","1100–Male":"1100–Deceased","1213":"1213","1235":"1235","1100":"1100","1220":"1220","1262":"1262","1162":"1162","1318":"1318","Headington, Oxfordshire, England":"Headington, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Berkhamstead Castle, Hertfordshire, England":"Croft Ambrey, Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Basset","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from a diminutive of Old French <i>bas(se)</i> ‘short, of low stature’ (see   Bas  ).","English: variant of   Bassett  , a cognate of 1 above.","In some cases also an altered form of French <b>Besset</b> (see   Bessette   2). Compare   Bassette   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Bas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Mauricio, Abelardo, Florencio, Francisco, Jorge, Luis, Manuel, Pedro, Soledad, Vicente.  Eastern Slavic Dmytro, Liya, Pyotr, Sergey.","Catalan: habitational name from a place so named in the district of La Garrotxa, Catalonia.","Basque: topographic name for someone who lived by a wood, from <i>baso</i> ‘wood, forest’."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Basset was born in 1162, in Headington, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Basset. She married Sir William de Courtenay about 1238. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1213, in Croft Ambrey, Herefordshire, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1162–1213":"1162–1213","1220–1262":"1220–1262","1235–1318":"1235–1318","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1213":"1213","1235":"1235","1100":"1100","1220":"1220","1262":"1262","1162":"1162","1318":"1318","Headington, Oxfordshire, England":"Headington, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Berkhamstead Castle, Hertfordshire, England":"Croft Ambrey, Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"1162–1213":"1162–1213","1220–1262":"1220–1262","1235–1318":"1235–1318","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1213":"1213","1235":"1235","1100":"1100","1220":"1220","1262":"1262","1162":"1162","1318":"1318","Headington, Oxfordshire, England":"Headington, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","